# Collaboration workflow

Two people share `main`. These conventions keep it clean and keep previews meaningful.

## Branching
- Never commit directly to `main`. Branch first.
- Branch names: `feature/<short-desc>`, `fix/<short-desc>`, `chore/<short-desc>`. Keep them short and hyphenated.
- Pull `main` before starting a branch, and again before opening the PR, so you rebase on the latest.
- Keep PRs small and focused. One feature or fix per PR is far easier to review than a mega-branch.

## Commits
- Imperative present tense: "Add hero section", "Fix canonical on blog index", not "added" or "fixing".
- One logical change per commit where practical. No secrets, no commented-out debris.

## Definition of done (before opening a PR)
- [ ] `next build` passes locally.
- [ ] `next lint` passes with no new warnings.
- [ ] For any new or changed page, the `@60-page-checklist` has been run.
- [ ] No secrets or `.env*` files staged.
- [ ] The branch's Vercel preview URL has been opened and the change verified on the rendered page.

## Review and merge
- Open a pull request and let the other person glance at it before merging to `main`. For a two-person team a quick review beats none.
- Merge via the PR, then delete the branch.
- **Never force-push a shared branch or `main`.** Force-push is only ever acceptable on your own un-shared branch that nobody else has pulled.
